---
import CaseLayout from '../layouts/CaseLayout.astro';
import ReaderColumn from '../components/reader/ReaderColumn.astro';
import Hero from '../components/reader/Hero.astro';
import MetaRow from '../components/reader/MetaRow.astro';
import Section from '../components/reader/Section.astro';
import SectionLabel from '../components/reader/SectionLabel.astro';
import H2 from '../components/reader/H2.astro';
import Lead from '../components/reader/Lead.astro';
import Body from '../components/reader/Body.astro';
import Callout from '../components/reader/Callout.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/reader/PullQuote.astro';
import MarginRef from '../components/reader/MarginRef.astro';
import Hr from '../components/reader/Hr.astro';
import Outcome from '../components/reader/Outcome.astro';
import EndRow from '../components/reader/EndRow.astro';
import ImgSlot from '../components/reader/ImgSlot.astro';
import OpeningTransition from '../components/canvas/OpeningTransition.astro';
---

<CaseLayout title="Cockpit View 2.0 — Sivanesh TV" caseNum="01" caseName="Cockpit View 2.0">
  <Fragment slot="opening">
    <OpeningTransition caption='Cockpit View <em>2.0</em>'>
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 300" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="80%">
        <g stroke="#d8352a" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity=".8">
          <circle cx="200" cy="150" r="100"/>
          <circle cx="200" cy="150" r="70" stroke-dasharray="2 4"/>
          <circle cx="200" cy="150" r="40"/>
          <line x1="200" y1="50" x2="200" y2="250"/>
          <line x1="100" y1="150" x2="300" y2="150"/>
        </g>
        <circle cx="200" cy="150" r="6" fill="#d8352a"/>
      </svg>
    </OpeningTransition>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="reader">
    <ReaderColumn>
      <Hero
        eyebrow="case study · 01"
        title='Cockpit View <em>2.0.</em>'
        sub="Redesigning the primary control interface for autonomous drone operations — from the ground up."
      />

      <MetaRow items={[
        { k: 'Role', v: 'Lead · with Prathamesh' },
        { k: 'Year', v: '2024' },
        { k: 'Scope', v: 'End-to-end UX · Design system' },
        { k: 'Tools', v: 'Figma · Framer · Claude Code' },
      ]} />

      <ImgSlot variant="hero"
        label="Image slot 01 · Hero shot"
        title="Full Cockpit View 2.0 interface"
        desc='A clean screenshot of the live UI — map, video feed, mission panel, system controls all visible. The "this is what it is" moment.'
        dims="16 : 10 · ideally 2400 × 1500 px"
        cap="Cockpit View 2.0 — in-flight, live telemetry"
        capMeta="the interface"
      />

      <!-- § 01 Context -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Context" num="§ 01" />
        <H2>Cockpit View is the <em>primary interface</em> operators live in all day.</H2>
        <Lead>It runs entirely in a browser — no native app, no dedicated hardware — and it has to perform like both a map and a command centre simultaneously. When we inherited the design, it worked. But "working" and "trustworthy" aren't the same thing at this scale.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>Professional drone operators use Cockpit View to control autonomous flights, monitor live video, manage missions, and respond to in-flight events. Every shift is hours long. Every alert matters. Every moment of ambiguity in the interface translates into cognitive load the operator can't afford.</p>
          <p>The v1 interface was built for a single drone. By the time I joined, operators were running multiple sites, responding to alerts from integrations fired at any hour, and beginning to prepare for regulatory one-to-many waivers. The interface hadn't caught up.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <!-- § 02 The problem -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The problem" num="§ 02" />
        <PullQuote>The interface was working. The <em>operators</em> were doing the work it should have been doing.</PullQuote>
        <Body>
          <p>When we sat in on CS calls and read the transcripts, a pattern emerged. Operators were compensating — memorising which panel held which control, ignoring alerts they'd learned to filter out, opening multiple browser tabs to "see everything at once." The interface wasn't broken. It was offloading its work onto the person using it.</p>
          <p>The hard part wasn't identifying this. The hard part was <strong>deciding what to change first</strong> when the answer was <em>everything is coupled to everything</em>.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p>Information architecture is the spine. Before we could fix any screen, we had to decide where everything should <em>live</em>, and why. That became the first of four structural rewrites.</p></Callout>
        <MarginRef jump="alerts">↗ see the alert-system redesign</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          label="Image slot 02 · Evidence"
          title="v1 interface, annotated"
          desc="A screenshot of the old Cockpit (v1) with arrows/sticky annotations showing what operators were compensating for. Red pen marks where panels collapsed or alerts got buried. Or: a photo of an actual operator setup with multiple tabs."
          dims="16 : 9 · ideally 2200 × 1240 px"
          cap={'v1 — the "it works" version operators were working around'}
          capMeta="before"
        />
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 03 Step one (IA) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step one" num="§ 03" />
        <H2>Before designing anything, decide where everything <em>lives</em> — and why.</H2>
        <Lead>The first structural decision wasn't visual. It was categorical.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>We mapped every piece of information, every action, every state across the old interface — then sorted them into three buckets based on a simple test: does the operator need this to <em>monitor</em>, to <em>act</em>, or to <em>diagnose</em>? Everything got one bucket. No exceptions.</p>
          <p>That single rule eliminated the question of where to put things. Monitoring information (live video, telemetry, map state) became the always-visible surface. Action controls (mission dispatch, manual override, emergency stop) became the ever-ready toolbar. Diagnostic data (logs, history, settings) moved to on-demand panels. The operator now knew where to look without thinking — which is exactly what matters when there's no time to think.</p>
        </Body>
        <MarginRef jump="ia-diagram">↗ see the IA diagram</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          label="Image slot 03 · Information architecture"
          title="The three-bucket sort"
          desc="A clean IA diagram showing every element of the UI sorted into Monitor / Act / Diagnose. Could be a Figma export, or an annotated screenshot mapping the actual live UI to the three zones."
          dims="16 : 9 · ideally 2000 × 1125 px"
          cap="Information architecture — monitor, act, diagnose"
          capMeta="the rule"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 04 Step two (Alerts) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step two" num="§ 04" />
        <H2>If the alerts panel is empty, <em>that</em> should feel like good news.</H2>
        <Lead>v1 buried alerts. Low-priority warnings, critical emergencies, informational nudges — all stacked in the same list. Operators had learned to ignore them.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>We rebuilt the alert system with three levels — <strong>critical, warning, informational</strong> — each with a distinct visual grammar, a distinct sound, and a distinct action model. Critical alerts take over the interface until acknowledged. Warnings persist until resolved. Informational alerts fade after a beat.</p>
          <p>More importantly: the alert panel now tells you when it's empty. A quiet green state, explicit and visible. An empty panel should feel like a <em>status</em>, not an absence.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p>"If there's nothing to worry about, say so. Don't leave the operator wondering whether the alert system is broken."</p></Callout>
        <MarginRef jump="alerts">↗ see the alert severity diagram</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          label="Image slot 04 · Alert system"
          title="Three severities, in context"
          desc='Screenshot stack showing all three states: (1) Critical takeover overlay, (2) Warning persistent badge, (3) Informational fade. Plus the empty-state "all nominal" green state. Ideally shown within the actual Cockpit chrome.'
          dims="16 : 9 · ideally 2000 × 1125 px"
          cap="Alert grammar — critical, warning, informational, nominal"
          capMeta="the system"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 05 Step three (Feedback) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step three" num="§ 05" />
        <H2>One question per system. <em>Three questions</em> total.</H2>
        <Lead>Every piece of feedback in the interface — every status indicator, every confirmation, every animation — now answers one of three questions, and only one.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Is the connection healthy?</strong> Answered by the always-visible network glyph at the top-right. Red if the drone has lost link. Amber if degraded. Green if nominal.</p>
          <p><strong>Is the command understood?</strong> Answered by a micro-interaction at the action point. The button dims. A dot pulses. A confirmation appears <em>at the location of the action</em>, not somewhere else on screen.</p>
          <p><strong>Is the drone doing what I asked?</strong> Answered by the map and telemetry together, updating in sync. If they ever disagree, we show the disagreement explicitly rather than picking a winner.</p>
        </Body>

        <ImgSlot variant="square"
          label="Image slot 05 · Feedback micro-states"
          title="Three questions, three indicators"
          desc="Close-up zooms of the three indicators — network glyph states (red / amber / green), the command-confirm micro-interaction at the action point, and the map/telemetry sync state. Ideally a single composed image showing all three."
          dims="4 : 3 · ideally 1600 × 1200 px"
          cap="Feedback architecture — one question per system"
          capMeta="the grammar"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 06 Step four (Layout) -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="Step four" num="§ 06" />
        <H2>A layout that earns operator trust by <em>never</em> surprising them.</H2>
        <Lead>The biggest complaint with v1 wasn't what things did — it was that things <em>moved</em>. Panels re-sized depending on what was active. Controls appeared and disappeared. The operator never developed muscle memory.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>v2 uses a fixed layout grammar. Four zones: map (left), video feed (right), mission panel (bottom-left), system controls (bottom-right). Nothing ever moves. Zones can expand or collapse for emphasis, but their positions are permanent. The operator's hand knows where to go before their eyes confirm it.</p>
          <p>This sounds boring. It is boring. Boring is the entire point.</p>
        </Body>

        <ImgSlot variant="split"
          halves={[
            { label: 'Image slot 06a · Before', title: 'v1 layout', desc: 'Old Cockpit screenshot, showing panels that resize/move.', dims: '~1200 × 900 px' },
            { label: 'Image slot 06b · After', title: 'v2 layout', desc: 'New Cockpit screenshot, showing fixed 4-zone grammar.', dims: '~1200 × 900 px' },
          ]}
        />
        <p style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:10px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);text-align:center;margin-top:-18px;margin-bottom:24px">— the single most important image in this case —</p>
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 07 Outcomes -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What happened" num="§ 07" />
        <H2>The receipts.</H2>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          label="Image slot 07 · Outcome visual"
          title="In production, in use"
          desc={"One of: (a) photo of Cockpit 2.0 on a real operator's monitor during a shift, (b) a Loom thumbnail or embedded video of a live demo, (c) a quote from a CS lead or operator, stylised as a pull-quote graphic."}
          dims="16 : 9 · ideally 2000 × 1125 px"
          cap="Cockpit View 2.0 — live in enterprise deployments"
          capMeta="evidence"
        />

        <Outcome items={[
          { n: 'Live', l: 'Deployed', d: 'Cockpit View 2.0 shipped as the primary interface across FlytBase enterprise deployments.' },
          { n: '3×', l: 'Fewer support calls', d: "About alert ambiguity and layout confusion, based on CS's tracking over 2024 Q4." },
          { n: '1→N', l: 'Scaled', d: 'The layout and IA foundations carried over directly into Fleet View — the next case.' },
        ]} />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 08 Reflection -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What I took away" num="§ 08" />
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Structural rewrites need a rule, not a vision.</strong> "Everything has one bucket" survived every design review. A mood board wouldn't have.</p>
          <p><strong>Operators design the interface with you.</strong> Shadowing CS calls and reading transcripts isn't a substitute for user research — it's where most of the real insight came from. The people closest to the user knew the answer; I just had to listen.</p>
          <p><strong>Boring is a feature.</strong> In critical-ops interfaces, "surprising" is almost always bad. The best thing you can do for the operator is build an interface they can forget about.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <EndRow note="— end of case · § 01 / 02 —" nextLabel="Next: Fleet View ↗" nextHref="/fleet" />
    </ReaderColumn>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="artifacts">
    <!-- §00 wayfinding markers -->
    <div class="marker md red artifact" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="-80" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="200" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-8deg);font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:34px;line-height:1.1;color:var(--marker-red)">↓ read straight through</div>
    <div class="marker sm black artifact" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="-40" data-side="right" data-gap="40" data-width="180" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(4deg);font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:18px;line-height:1.1;color:var(--ink)">drag around to<br>explore →</div>

    <!-- §02 stickies -->
    <div class="sticky pink artifact" data-anchor="1" data-anchor-offset="40" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="280" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-4deg);width:280px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:#ff8fa3;box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— operator, multi-monitor setup —</div>
      "I have Cockpit in one tab, alerts in another, video feed pinned separately. <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">That's my workflow.</em>"
    </div>

    <div class="sticky artifact" data-anchor="1" data-anchor-offset="360" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="260" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(3deg);width:260px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:var(--yellow);box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— what we found —</div>
      Every feature added a panel. Every panel fought for screen space. The operator paid the <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">cognitive tax.</em>
    </div>

    <!-- §03 principle + diagram -->
    <div class="principle artifact" data-anchor="2" data-anchor-offset="20" data-side="right" data-gap="80" data-width="380" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(1.5deg);width:380px;padding:32px 32px 28px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:3px 5px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.06),6px 14px 28px rgba(40,35,25,.2);border:1px solid rgba(40,35,25,.08)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-12px;right:10%;width:90px;height:22px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(3deg);box-shadow:0 2px 6px rgba(40,35,25,.1)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--red);margin-bottom:14px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px"><span>◆</span>the interaction rule every tool obeys</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-weight:700;font-size:26px;line-height:1.15;letter-spacing:-.02em;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:10px"><em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--red)">Push</em> or <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--red)">Overlay.</em> Every tool picks one.</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-size:13px;line-height:1.55;color:var(--ink-2);margin-bottom:14px">Tools that need ambient awareness (Mission, GTL, AI-R Detections) <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--ink)">push</em> the body — they squeeze other components and share the space. Tools that need momentary focus (Options, Scheduler, Team Chat) <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--ink)">overlay</em> — they sit on top briefly and dismiss.</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:600;font-size:17px;color:var(--ink-3);padding-top:12px;border-top:1px dashed rgba(40,35,25,.18)">— the IA of a complex cockpit</div>
    </div>

    <!-- §03 panel hierarchy diagram -->
    <div id="obj-ia-diagram" data-label="The Cockpit layout" class="diagram artifact" data-anchor="2" data-anchor-offset="480" data-side="right" data-gap="60" data-width="460" style="position:absolute;width:460px;transform:rotate(-1deg);padding:24px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:2px 3px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.04),4px 8px 20px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-10px;left:40%;width:60px;height:20px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(-3deg)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:4px">The Cockpit layout</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:16px">— body · left panel · right panel —</div>
      <svg viewBox="0 0 420 280" width="100%"><rect x="10" y="10" width="400" height="28" fill="none" stroke="#1a1a1c" stroke-width="1"/><text x="210" y="28" text-anchor="middle" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="9" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing="1">TOP BAR · DEVICE · ALERTS · PROFILE</text><rect x="10" y="48" width="60" height="190" fill="none" stroke="#d8352a" stroke-width="1.2"/><text x="40" y="72" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Caveat" font-size="14" fill="#d8352a" font-weight="700">LEFT</text><g font-family="Inter" font-size="9" fill="#4a4945" text-anchor="middle"><text x="40" y="100">Terrain</text><text x="40" y="115">RTK</text><text x="40" y="130">Dock</text><text x="40" y="145">Network</text><text x="40" y="160">Parachute</text></g><text x="40" y="225" text-anchor="middle" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing="1">HIGH-FREQ</text><rect x="80" y="48" width="260" height="190" fill="none" stroke="#1a1a1c" stroke-width="1.5"/><text x="210" y="72" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Caveat" font-size="14" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="700">BODY</text><g font-family="Inter" font-size="10" fill="#4a4945" text-anchor="middle"><text x="210" y="115">Map · Video feed</text><text x="210" y="135">Control panel</text><text x="210" y="155">(Dock · FPV · Aux feeds)</text></g><text x="210" y="225" text-anchor="middle" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing="1">PRIMARY WORK</text><rect x="350" y="48" width="60" height="190" fill="none" stroke="#d8352a" stroke-width="1.2"/><text x="380" y="72" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Caveat" font-size="14" fill="#d8352a" font-weight="700">RIGHT</text><g font-family="Inter" font-size="9" fill="#4a4945" text-anchor="middle"><text x="380" y="100">Mission</text><text x="380" y="115">GTL</text><text x="380" y="130">POI</text><text x="380" y="145">AI-R</text><text x="380" y="160">Flinks</text></g><text x="380" y="225" text-anchor="middle" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing="1">DEEP ACTIONS</text><text x="210" y="268" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Caveat" font-size="13" fill="#d8352a" font-weight="700">each panel has a job. nothing overflows.</text></svg>
    </div>

    <!-- §04 alert diagram -->
    <div id="obj-alerts" data-label="The Alerts Bar" class="diagram artifact" data-anchor="3" data-anchor-offset="40" data-side="right" data-gap="60" data-width="440" style="position:absolute;width:440px;transform:rotate(-1deg);padding:24px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:2px 3px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.04),4px 8px 20px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-10px;left:40%;width:60px;height:20px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(-3deg)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:4px">The Alerts Bar</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:16px">— four categories · one surface · always visible —</div>
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 220" width="100%"><rect x="10" y="20" width="95" height="52" fill="none" stroke="#d8352a" stroke-width="1.5"/><circle cx="24" cy="40" r="5" fill="#d8352a"/><text x="34" y="44" font-family="Inter" font-size="11" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="700">Airspace</text><text x="18" y="60" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing=".5">NFZ · NOTAM · UTM</text><rect x="115" y="20" width="95" height="52" fill="none" stroke="#f5a524" stroke-width="1.5"/><circle cx="129" cy="40" r="5" fill="#f5a524"/><text x="139" y="44" font-family="Inter" font-size="11" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="700">Diagnostics</text><text x="123" y="60" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing=".5">HMS · LINK · BATTERY</text><rect x="220" y="20" width="95" height="52" fill="none" stroke="#4a9d5f" stroke-width="1.5"/><circle cx="234" cy="40" r="5" fill="#4a9d5f"/><text x="244" y="44" font-family="Inter" font-size="11" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="700">Weather</text><text x="228" y="60" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing=".5">WIND · RAIN · GUSTS</text><rect x="325" y="20" width="65" height="52" fill="none" stroke="#1a1a1c" stroke-width="1.2"/><circle cx="339" cy="40" r="5" fill="#1a1a1c"/><text x="349" y="44" font-family="Inter" font-size="11" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="700">System</text><text x="333" y="60" font-family="JetBrains Mono" font-size="7" fill="#7a7770" letter-spacing=".5">UPS · FW · CONFIG</text><text x="200" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Caveat" font-size="16" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="700">Every alert belongs to <tspan fill="#d8352a">one</tspan> category.</text><text x="200" y="125" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Inter" font-size="10" fill="#4a4945">Operator never wonders which system fired the warning.</text><g transform="translate(0 150)"><rect x="20" y="0" width="360" height="40" fill="rgba(245,200,74,.15)" stroke="#f5c84a" stroke-width=".8" stroke-dasharray="3 2"/><text x="200" y="17" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Inter" font-size="10" fill="#1a1a1c" font-weight="600">Progressive disclosure</text><text x="200" y="31" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Inter" font-size="9" fill="#4a4945">Secondary telemetry surfaces only when a severity trigger fires</text></g></svg>
    </div>

    <!-- §04 restraint sticky -->
    <div class="sticky artifact" data-anchor="3" data-anchor-offset="180" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="260" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(3deg);width:260px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:var(--yellow);box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— the restraint —</div>
      Left panel widgets are <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">silent</em> until severity demands they speak. No ambient noise.
    </div>

